So after her, things looked good.
I kept movin'.

252
00:30:51,075 --> 00:30:53,115
Now you can't stop?

253
00:30:57,332 --> 00:30:59,371
Here she is.

254
00:31:00,460 --> 00:31:02,499
Idaho Dream.

255
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:44,832
Did you see that?
A steelhead, man. Beautiful.

256
00:31:46,506 --> 00:31:48,831
Aah... Did you see that?

257
00:31:49,551 --> 00:31:51,590
Yeah.

258
00:31:52,428 --> 00:31:56,509
Well, my good friend, we're broke.
Do you have any suggestions?

259
00:31:58,184 --> 00:32:02,562
If I knew what you know,
I'd never be broke.

260
00:32:02,689 --> 00:32:07,267
What do you <i>think</i> I know
that you would <i>like</i> to know?

261
00:32:07,402 --> 00:32:09,441
All right...

262
00:32:11,614 --> 00:32:16,775
For one thing, I'd like to know
if there's a good way of beating a bank.

263
00:32:16,911 --> 00:32:19,581
Banks! What do you know about banks?

264
00:32:19,706 --> 00:32:22,078
What the hell do <i>you</i> know about banks?

265
00:32:26,337 --> 00:32:27,369
What's so funny?

266
00:32:27,505 --> 00:32:28,750
- You.
- Me?

267
00:32:28,882 --> 00:32:30,921
That's right.

268
00:32:32,260 --> 00:32:35,131
A man can do
whatever he sets his mind to.

269
00:32:35,263 --> 00:32:40,423
Now, me, I wanna walk in
and buy a white Cadillac convertible.

270
00:32:40,560 --> 00:32:43,596
Actually walk in and buy it, cash.

271
00:33:09,589 --> 00:33:12,792
You might set your mind to gettin' us a lift.

272
00:33:13,676 --> 00:33:16,796
This walkin' is tough on my bad leg.

273
00:33:16,930 --> 00:33:21,093
This is the best time. Most State troopers
are having coffee now.

274
00:33:37,367 --> 00:33:39,406
Hey! Hey! Hey!

275
00:33:49,129 --> 00:33:51,999
That sure isn't any white Cadillac.

276
00:33:52,132 --> 00:33:54,089
Beggars can't be choosy.

277
00:33:54,217 --> 00:33:57,218
You simple-minded sonofabitch.

278
00:34:01,641 --> 00:34:03,219
Get in the back seat.

279
00:34:03,351 --> 00:34:06,802
- There's a raccoon in here.
- Hell with that. Get in the back.

280
00:34:06,938 --> 00:34:11,517
What's the matter with you?
I ain't got all day to wait on you. Come on.

281
00:34:19,451 --> 00:34:22,487
I've been...
I'll take you wherever you wanna go.

282
00:34:22,620 --> 00:34:25,194
I've been drivin' all over this country.

283
00:34:25,331 --> 00:34:28,582
This guy another friend of yours?

284
00:34:28,710 --> 00:34:30,786
Slightly advanced, isn't he?

285
00:34:49,814 --> 00:34:53,942
Hey, what's wrong with this wreck?
We're gettin' gassed back here.

286
00:35:03,787 --> 00:35:07,950
This guy's a basket case.
He's got the exhaust pipe in here.

287
00:35:30,647 --> 00:35:36,483
- He's not your run-of-the-mill basket case.
- This guy is definitely out to lunch.

288
00:35:47,205 --> 00:35:50,040
What the hell's the matter with you, boy?

289
00:35:54,087 --> 00:35:58,085
Hey, you're good, man. Very good.

290
00:35:58,800 --> 00:36:00,839
Glass head, like all these nuts.

291
00:36:04,139 --> 00:36:07,009
I don't know what we're gonna do
with these rabbits.

292
00:36:07,142 --> 00:36:09,181
Get 'em out.

293
00:36:10,937 --> 00:36:12,977
I saw that. That was very good.

294
00:36:13,898 --> 00:36:16,816
Where are we headed, man? I'm ready.

295
00:36:16,943 --> 00:36:21,901
I don't know. Sometimes when there's
nothin' to do, it's best to keep movin'.

296
00:36:23,450 --> 00:36:25,489
You smell somethin' up here?

297
00:36:26,661 --> 00:36:28,321
No.

298
00:36:28,455 --> 00:36:30,910
- Smell that?
- I don't smell anything.

299
00:36:32,792 --> 00:36:34,832
It smells like shit.

300
00:36:35,879 --> 00:36:37,918
Ah...

301
00:36:38,214 --> 00:36:40,254
- Raccoon shit.
- Raccoon shit.

302
00:36:41,092 --> 00:36:44,508
Hang your hand out the window
and let the rain get at it.

303
00:36:44,637 --> 00:36:46,963
- Would you like...
- Get outta here!

304
00:36:47,098 --> 00:36:49,470
Just remember not to pick your teeth.

305
00:36:51,478 --> 00:36:53,351
Oh, God...

306
00:37:33,686 --> 00:37:38,645
In small-town banks, they leave the
telephone off the hook in the vault at night

307
00:37:38,775 --> 00:37:41,064
so the local operator can listen in.

308
00:37:42,320 --> 00:37:48,405
People walk into these banks with paper
sacks, fill 'em with money and walk out.

309
00:37:48,535 --> 00:37:51,026
Anybody can do it.

310
00:37:51,162 --> 00:37:52,740
Bullshit.

311
00:37:59,462 --> 00:38:03,923
The newest bank vaults have walls
of reinforced concrete five feet thick,

312
00:38:04,050 --> 00:38:06,802
backed by six inches of steel.

313
00:38:06,928 --> 00:38:09,597
The vault door is stainless steel-faced.

314
00:38:09,722 --> 00:38:15,309
It's an inch and a half of cast steel,
another 12 inches of burn-resisting steel,

315
00:38:15,437 --> 00:38:19,600
and another inch and a half
of open-hearthed steel.

316
00:38:19,732 --> 00:38:21,772
Come here.

317
00:38:22,569 --> 00:38:26,401
A vault door has 20 bolts,
each an inch in diameter.

318
00:38:26,531 --> 00:38:29,152
Eight on each side,
two top and two bottom.

319
00:38:29,284 --> 00:38:34,159
This holds the door into a 16-inch steel
jamb set in 18 inches of concrete.

320
00:38:34,289 --> 00:38:39,081
It's crosshatched by steel bars
running both vertical and horizontal.

321
00:38:39,210 --> 00:38:45,664
This door is precision-made so you can't
pour nitro between the door and the vault.

322
00:38:45,800 --> 00:38:47,840
If that isn't enough,

323
00:38:49,012 --> 00:38:51,419
there's microphones, electric eyes,

324
00:38:51,556 --> 00:38:55,636
pressure-sensitive mats,
vibration detectors, tear gas,

325
00:38:55,769 --> 00:39:00,561
and even thermostats that detect
the slightest rise in temperature.

326
00:39:00,690 --> 00:39:02,564
Still interested in banks?

327
00:39:02,692 --> 00:39:05,646
I knew you weren't a preacher.

328
00:39:05,779 --> 00:39:08,982
Preaching isn't so bad. You get used to it.

329
00:39:09,115 --> 00:39:14,026
You are what you do, so to speak.
At times I even forgot about the money.

330
00:39:14,162 --> 00:39:16,783
What money?

331
00:39:20,335 --> 00:39:22,374
Montana Armored.

332
00:39:23,755 --> 00:39:25,794
Montana Armored?

333
00:39:27,425 --> 00:39:29,465
How did you get into the vault?

334
00:39:31,262 --> 00:39:35,011
20mm canon with armour-piercing shells.
Wasn't too hard.

335
00:39:36,142 --> 00:39:38,633
That was on the news.
That was a big deal.

336
00:39:38,770 --> 00:39:41,687
What did they call that guy?
The Thunderbolt.

337
00:39:45,193 --> 00:39:47,232
That's you.

338
00:39:47,403 --> 00:39:49,692
You're the Thunderbolt.

339
00:39:49,823 --> 00:39:51,981
Parson's luck.

340
00:39:52,117 --> 00:39:53,575
Oh, no!

341
00:39:53,701 --> 00:39:55,741
Watch out for the dog shit.

342
00:39:56,830 --> 00:40:02,784
Thunderbolt! Thunderbolt and Lightfoot.
That sounds like somethin'.

343
00:40:02,919 --> 00:40:05,588
You're forgetting I'm a lot older than you.

344
00:40:05,713 --> 00:40:08,002
There are plenty of guys twice my age

345
00:40:08,133 --> 00:40:10,209
who don't know their ass
from a hole in the ground.

346
00:40:10,343 --> 00:40:11,968
In for a penny, in for a pound.

347
00:40:12,095 --> 00:40:15,049
So, who were these guys
that are following us?

348
00:40:15,181 --> 00:40:17,221
Oh...

349
00:40:17,350 --> 00:40:20,221
The big dude's a war hero.

350
00:40:20,353 --> 00:40:23,603
Name's Red Leary.
Saved my life once in Korea.

351
00:40:23,731 --> 00:40:27,812
He was sent to prison in Illinois
later on for stabbing a woman.

352
00:40:27,944 --> 00:40:31,111
There he met an old-time bank robber,
Billy Lamb.

353
00:40:31,239 --> 00:40:34,489
Lamb taught him how to break safes.

354
00:40:34,617 --> 00:40:37,654
Lamb was a real genius for organisation.

355
00:40:37,787 --> 00:40:39,827
Thanks.

356
00:40:41,749 --> 00:40:46,577
When they got out, Lamb introduced him
to Dunlop, an electronics expert.

357
00:40:46,713 --> 00:40:49,464
That's the guy you took care of
in the field.

358
00:40:51,801 --> 00:40:53,794
- Wanna brew?
- Definitely.

359
00:40:53,928 --> 00:40:58,721
The little Orphan Annie-eyed
character's Eddie Goody.

360
00:40:58,850 --> 00:41:01,388
He's a driver.
Harmless when he's alone.

361
00:41:01,519 --> 00:41:03,726
So what happened to the money?

362
00:41:03,855 --> 00:41:07,639
Hey, I don't care anything
about the money, you know that.

363
00:41:07,776 --> 00:41:10,267
We're friends. I like you as a friend.

364
00:41:10,403 --> 00:41:12,443
Yeah.

365
00:41:14,532 --> 00:41:21,614
We hid it in a one-room schoolhouse
in Warsaw, a place Lamb went to as a kid.

366
00:41:21,748 --> 00:41:26,873
Hid it in a wall behind the blackboard.
Half a million dollars worth. It's still there.

367
00:41:27,003 --> 00:41:29,541
- Schoolhouse?
- Behind the blackboard.

368
00:41:29,672 --> 00:41:31,712
Why?

369
00:41:32,509 --> 00:41:36,886
It was always Lamb's practice
to control the money till the final split.

370
00:41:37,013 --> 00:41:41,011
We kept in contact with each other
through personals in the paper.

371
00:41:41,142 --> 00:41:45,187
Then Lamb had a heart attack and died.
Guess he was just too old for it.

372
00:41:45,313 --> 00:41:49,525
Leary got suspicious but I didn't
tell him where the money was because

373
00:41:49,651 --> 00:41:52,486
I knew he'd go straight to it,
heat or no heat.

374
00:41:55,323 --> 00:42:01,029
Then the police released a thing in the
press saying the money had been found.

375
00:42:01,162 --> 00:42:02,277
Bullshit.

376
00:42:02,413 --> 00:42:04,287
Leary went off his ass.

377
00:42:05,458 --> 00:42:08,625
He got careless
but couldn't lead them to the money

378
00:42:08,753 --> 00:42:10,793
cos he didn't know where it was.

379
00:42:12,090 --> 00:42:17,962
Finally, they convicted him on another
bank robbery that took place years before.

380
00:42:18,096 --> 00:42:22,259
And when he got out
he convinced the others I'd set him up.

381
00:42:22,392 --> 00:42:25,642
I decided
best that I should drop out for a while.

382
00:42:28,273 --> 00:42:30,645
That church was a pretty far-out idea.

383
00:42:31,651 --> 00:42:34,569
About as far out as possible, I thought.

384
00:43:18,740 --> 00:43:20,779
Are you sure this is the spot?

385
00:43:22,076 --> 00:43:23,156
Yeah.

386
00:43:23,286 --> 00:43:27,118
- What? I didn't hear what you said.
- I said, yeah, this is it.

387
00:43:30,794 --> 00:43:32,833
Well, what happened to it?

388
00:43:33,797 --> 00:43:35,836
I don't know. Progress.

389
00:44:07,205 --> 00:44:09,244
Have a nice day, boy.

390
00:44:11,126 --> 00:44:13,284
Here, for you.

391
00:44:13,419 --> 00:44:15,459
That's the last of our money.

392
00:44:17,841 --> 00:44:20,510
It's good. Real good.

393
00:44:48,079 --> 00:44:50,119
Fantastic pistachio.

394
00:44:52,041 --> 00:44:53,833
What do we do now?

395
00:44:53,960 --> 00:44:56,533
Drop your cocks
and reach for your socks.

396
00:44:58,548 --> 00:45:01,217
Don't look at me. I didn't say a word.

397
00:45:01,342 --> 00:45:03,382
- Red?
- Start the car.

398
00:45:04,971 --> 00:45:08,885
Freeze, you sonofabitch.
The first one of you moves, I shoot.

399
00:45:44,761 --> 00:45:49,008
All right, kill the engine.
Hand me the keys and don't turn around.

400
00:45:51,559 --> 00:45:53,931
Both of you get out Pistachio's side.

401
00:45:54,062 --> 00:45:58,273
No ideas - you'll both be dead
before you hit the ground.

402
00:45:58,399 --> 00:45:59,313
Move it.

403
00:46:12,122 --> 00:46:13,699
Turn around.

404
00:46:16,084 --> 00:46:18,539
The guys in the car.

405
00:46:18,670 --> 00:46:20,709
That's it, smartass.

406
00:46:21,840 --> 00:46:23,749
Red. Goody.

407
00:46:24,717 --> 00:46:28,051
- How's Dunlop?
- That's for us to know and you to find out.

408
00:46:28,179 --> 00:46:30,006
Shut up, Goody.

409
00:46:32,684 --> 00:46:35,720
- What do you want, Red?
- What do I want?

410
00:46:35,854 --> 00:46:40,017
You got balls, I'll say that for you, Johnny.
I want your ass, my friend.

411
00:46:40,150 --> 00:46:43,269
Hey, flattery's not gonna
get you guys anywhere.

412
00:46:44,571 --> 00:46:47,488
- Who's the comedian?
- Name's Lightfoot.

413
00:46:47,615 --> 00:46:48,813
Does he know everything?

414
00:46:48,950 --> 00:46:50,409
- No.
- Yeah.

415
00:46:54,747 --> 00:46:56,954
Lightfoot, huh?

416
00:46:57,083 --> 00:46:57,997
Yeah.

417
00:47:06,926 --> 00:47:10,011
Good thing I didn't hit him in the face.
He'd be dead now.

418
00:47:10,138 --> 00:47:13,139
You always had a high opinion
of yourself, Red.

419
00:47:13,266 --> 00:47:15,757
What you been preachin' lately, Johnny?

420
00:47:15,894 --> 00:47:17,933
Survival.

421
00:47:20,482 --> 00:47:21,762
Are you ready?

422
00:47:21,900 --> 00:47:23,939
I've been countin' the days.

423
00:47:34,037 --> 00:47:36,113
That's for the kid.

424
00:47:36,247 --> 00:47:40,708
- You wanna talk or play games?
- What do you want me to do, Red?

425
00:47:41,211 --> 00:47:43,250
Shut your face.

426
00:48:01,648 --> 00:48:03,854
I can't breathe! I got asthma.

427
00:48:06,152 --> 00:48:08,275
What do you want me to do now, Red?

428
00:48:08,404 --> 00:48:10,397
Kill the sonofabitch.

429
00:48:10,532 --> 00:48:12,109
Here?

430
00:48:12,242 --> 00:48:13,700
Yes.

431
00:48:13,827 --> 00:48:14,692
Now?

432
00:48:15,286 --> 00:48:16,449
Now!

433
00:48:18,289 --> 00:48:21,908
Don't ever point a gun at me.
Understand? Not even a twig.

434
00:48:23,002 --> 00:48:24,165
You got it.

435
00:48:24,295 --> 00:48:26,418
You come from hitters, don't you?

436
00:48:31,302 --> 00:48:35,632
What are you waitin' for? Why don't you
kill me? I woulda killed you.

437
00:48:44,149 --> 00:48:47,897
That doesn't make up for two years.
I'm gonna kill you anyway.

438
00:48:48,027 --> 00:48:50,518
The money was here - in the schoolhouse.

439
00:48:53,158 --> 00:48:56,194
What's this garbage talking about?

440
00:48:56,327 --> 00:48:58,997
The money was never recovered.

441
00:48:59,998 --> 00:49:04,576
TV, radio, papers, everybody was lying.
They were working with the police.

442
00:49:04,711 --> 00:49:09,254
When Lamb died I never came back here.
The money's still here. It's safe.

443
00:49:09,382 --> 00:49:11,173
Here?

444
00:49:11,301 --> 00:49:16,176
Yeah. Lamb went to school here in
Warsaw, a little one-room schoolhouse.

445
00:49:16,306 --> 00:49:19,223
We put the money in the wall,
behind the blackboard.

446
00:49:19,350 --> 00:49:22,387
Where's this one-room schoolhouse?

447
00:49:22,520 --> 00:49:24,098
Gone.

448
00:49:24,230 --> 00:49:26,270
Gone? Gone where?

449
00:49:29,068 --> 00:49:32,852
I wish I knew. Used to be right
where the new schoolhouse is now.

450
00:49:32,989 --> 00:49:35,860
You expect me to believe all this crap?

451
00:49:36,993 --> 00:49:41,073
It's the truth. Why do you think
I'd come to a dumb town like this?

452
00:49:41,206 --> 00:49:44,871
How the hell do I know?
You're queer for dumb towns.

453
00:49:45,001 --> 00:49:47,290
Half a million dollars don't disappear.

454
00:49:47,420 --> 00:49:50,540
They shoulda found something
when they tore the place down.

455
00:49:50,673 --> 00:49:52,713
I wish I had the answer for you.

456
00:49:56,805 --> 00:49:59,378
The sad part is that we got away with it.

457
00:50:00,975 --> 00:50:03,015
It's a sin, that's what it is.

458
00:50:04,104 --> 00:50:06,143
Christ, it's a sin.

459
00:50:07,565 --> 00:50:10,235
Oh, boy, I feel old.

460
00:50:12,153 --> 00:50:14,395
What are we gonna do now, Red?

461
00:50:14,531 --> 00:50:16,570
Shut up, Goody.

462
00:50:20,620 --> 00:50:22,660
I got hay fever too.

463
00:50:36,302 --> 00:50:39,588
- Why not do it again?
- What's he mouthin' off about?

464
00:50:39,722 --> 00:50:42,842
Montana Armored.
We hit the same place, the same way.

465
00:50:42,976 --> 00:50:45,015
Montana Armored?

466
00:50:49,274 --> 00:50:51,313
What?

467
00:50:52,277 --> 00:50:55,977
Hey, they'd never expect it.
Not something that big.

468
00:50:56,114 --> 00:50:58,984
It's never been done before, has it?

469
00:50:59,117 --> 00:51:02,367
That'd really be something, wouldn't it?

470
00:51:02,495 --> 00:51:04,535
Yeah, it sure would.

471
00:51:05,373 --> 00:51:07,449
Hey, I think that's a great idea.

472
00:51:07,584 --> 00:51:11,000
Let's not get queer over it.
What does the kid know anyway?

473
00:51:11,129 --> 00:51:13,999
Besides the Lamb is dead
and he wrecked Dunlop.

474
00:51:14,132 --> 00:51:18,509
You don't need the Lamb. We do it
the same way. You already did it once.

475
00:51:19,637 --> 00:51:21,215
You might have something.

476
00:51:21,347 --> 00:51:25,890
The blind leading the blind.
He's a kid. He eats pistachio ice cream.

477
00:51:26,019 --> 00:51:30,681
Jesus, you can lead a mule to water
but you can't make him drink it.

478
00:51:30,815 --> 00:51:33,223
That's a horse, not a mule.

479
00:51:33,359 --> 00:51:34,984
I agree.

480
00:51:35,111 --> 00:51:37,151
- Agree with what?
- With him.

481
00:51:38,156 --> 00:51:40,149
Good grief.

482
00:51:40,283 --> 00:51:44,660
Even if I did agree, what would we use
as a stake to operate with?

483
00:51:44,788 --> 00:51:48,157
Well, we could all get jobs for a while.

484
00:51:50,877 --> 00:51:54,293
You're better at asking questions
than you are at answering them.

485
00:51:56,132 --> 00:52:01,506
And the wolf shall dwell with the lamb and
the leopard shall lie down with the kid.

486
00:52:03,431 --> 00:52:04,925
What's that? A poem?

487
00:52:06,643 --> 00:52:08,552
No, it's a prayer.

488
00:52:59,070 --> 00:53:01,359
200 is 200 for the pot.

489
00:53:01,489 --> 00:53:02,948
200?

490
00:53:03,074 --> 00:53:08,413
Better than that piece of junk running out
on the highway. We got Goody's car still.

491
00:53:14,252 --> 00:53:16,825
The rich get richer, the poor get poorer.

492
00:53:18,006 --> 00:53:20,757
Where do you pick up
these pearis of wisdom?

493
00:53:20,884 --> 00:53:22,259
Books.

494
00:53:22,385 --> 00:53:25,172
You mean you can actually read?

495
00:53:25,930 --> 00:53:28,848
- I read <i>you</i> loud and clear.
- You better believe it.

496
00:53:28,975 --> 00:53:34,314
